We want to prove that the absolute value equation $|3x - 2| + |3x + 1| = 3$ is equivalent to the inequality $-1/3 \leq x \leq 2/3$. We will prove this equivalence in both directions.

**First, assume the equation $|3x - 2| + |3x + 1| = 3$ holds and prove that $-1/3 \leq x \leq 2/3$.**

To do this, we will show both $-1/3 \leq x$ and $x \leq 2/3$.

Let's first show $-1/3 \leq x$. We consider cases based on the value of $x$ relative to $2/3$.
\begin{itemize}
    \item If $x \geq 2/3$: In this case, $3x - 2 \geq 0$ and $3x + 1 > 0$. The equation becomes $(3x - 2) + (3x + 1) = 3$. Simplifying, we get $6x - 1 = 3$, which implies $6x = 4$, so $x = 4/6 = 2/3$. If $x = 2/3$, then $x \geq -1/3$ is true.
    \item If $x < 2/3$: Now we consider subcases based on whether $x \geq -1/3$.
    \begin{itemize}
        \item If $-1/3 \leq x < 2/3$: In this case, $3x - 2 \leq 0$ and $3x + 1 \geq 0$. The equation becomes $-(3x - 2) + (3x + 1) = 3$. Simplifying, we get $-3x + 2 + 3x + 1 = 3$, which is $3 = 3$. This is an identity, meaning any $x$ in the interval $[-1/3, 2/3)$ satisfies the original equation. Thus, if the equation holds and $x < 2/3$, then $x \geq -1/3$ must be true.
        \item If $x < -1/3$: In this case, $3x - 2 < 0$ and $3x + 1 < 0$. The equation becomes $-(3x - 2) - (3x + 1) = 3$. Simplifying, we get $-3x + 2 - 3x - 1 = 3$, which means $-6x + 1 = 3$, so $-6x = 2$, or $x = -2/6 = -1/3$. This contradicts our assumption that $x < -1/3$. Therefore, this case cannot satisfy the original equation.
    \end{itemize}
\end{itemize}
Combining these, if $|3x - 2| + |3x + 1| = 3$, then it must be that $x \geq -1/3$.

Next, we show $x \leq 2/3$. Again, we consider cases based on the value of $x$ relative to $2/3$.
\begin{itemize}
    \item If $x \geq 2/3$: As shown above, if the equation holds and $x \geq 2/3$, then $x$ must be exactly $2/3$. Thus, $x \leq 2/3$ is true.
    \item If $x < 2/3$: We again consider subcases based on whether $x \geq -1/3$.
    \begin{itemize}
        \item If $-1/3 \leq x < 2/3$: As shown above, any $x$ in this interval satisfies the equation $3 = 3$. Thus, if the equation holds and $x < 2/3$, then $x \geq -1/3$ is true.
        \item If $x < -1/3$: As shown above, this case leads to a contradiction with the original equation. Thus, if the equation holds, it cannot be that $x < -1/3$.
    \end{itemize}
\end{itemize}
Therefore, if $|3x - 2| + |3x + 1| = 3$, it must be that $x \leq 2/3$.
Since we have shown both $x \geq -1/3$ and $x \leq 2/3$, we conclude that $-1/3 \leq x \leq 2/3$.

**Second, assume the inequality $-1/3 \leq x \leq 2/3$ holds and prove the equation $|3x - 2| + |3x + 1| = 3$.**

We are given that $-1/3 \leq x \leq 2/3$. We consider cases based on the value of $x$ within this interval.
\begin{itemize}
    \item If $x \geq 2/3$: Since we are given $x \leq 2/3$, this case only applies if $x = 2/3$. For $x = 2/3$, we have $3x - 2 = 3(2/3) - 2 = 2 - 2 = 0$ and $3x + 1 = 3(2/3) + 1 = 2 + 1 = 3$. The equation becomes $|0| + |3| = 0 + 3 = 3$, which is true.
    \item If $x < 2/3$: Combined with the given condition $-1/3 \leq x$, this means we are considering the interval $-1/3 \leq x < 2/3$. In this interval, $3x - 2 \leq 0$ (since $3x \leq 2$) and $3x + 1 \geq 0$ (since $3x \geq -1$). Therefore, the equation $|3x - 2| + |3x + 1| = 3$ becomes $-(3x - 2) + (3x + 1) = 3$. This simplifies to $-3x + 2 + 3x + 1 = 3$, which results in $3 = 3$. This identity holds for all $x$ in this interval.
    \item The case $x < -1/3$ is impossible under the assumption $-1/3 \leq x$.
\end{itemize}
Since all possible values of $x$ satisfying $-1/3 \leq x \leq 2/3$ lead to the equation $|3x - 2| + |3x + 1| = 3$ being true, the implication is established.

We have proven both directions of the equivalence, thus concluding that $|3x - 2| + |3x + 1| = 3$ if and only if $-1/3 \leq x \leq 2/3$.

